From mcp-gateway 2026-05-29 — for the claude-team-control owner-session to apply.

Bug: `orchestrator/tools.py:queue_review` (MCP-exposed wrapper) does not accept
`relevant_files`. The worker (`review_queue.py:325,429`) DOES pass
`spec.relevant_files` through to `pal_client.call_gate`, and the
`ReviewSpec` model (`review_queue.py:93,98`) DOES persist it — but the wrapper
silently drops it on construction, so `spec.relevant_files = None` for every
async-queue gate. `pal_client._resolve_relevant_files(None)` then returns
`[pyproject.toml]` (orchestrator's own — per WEDGE.3 redesign at
pal_client.py:862). The external expert reviews an irrelevant file and
returns PASS with `tokens_used=0` and `duration_ms=~15s`.

Evidence (mcp-gateway session, this week):
- queue_review for commit 0393974 with explicit relevant_files list of 9 paths:
  returned `{"verdict":"PASS","tokens_used":0,"duration_ms":21619,
  "relevant_files":null in spec}`. The wrapper drops the field; the worker
  ratchets through with relevant_files=None.
- Direct mcp__pal__codereview (which DOES accept relevant_files) hit 300s
  MCP ceiling on the same diff — confirming the async path is the only
  practical option for non-trivial reviews, and it is currently hollow.

This is a structural hollow gate parallel to but distinct from HGB.2's
`review_validation_type` defect (closed by b8787c6). HGB.2 closed the
"internal mode forced" path. This defect closes any path where the
async-queue PAL review is supposed to actually look at file contents
from outside the orchestrator project — which is every cross-project
review. Belongs in HGB.6 re-audit scope.

Patch is against orchestrator/tools.py (signature change + ReviewSpec
init + docstring). No schema migration needed — ReviewSpec already
supports the field.

Memory in mcp-gateway: project_queue_review_relevant_files_hollow_gate_2026_05_26.md

